The Spark ecosystem consists of Spark Core for execution, Spark SQL for structured data processing, Structured Streaming for real-time processing,
MLlib for machine learning, and GraphX for graph processing. These components work together on top of Spark’s distributed architecture and integrate 
with storage systems and cluster managers


3) PySpark is faster than MapReduce because it processes data in memory and uses DAG-based execution instead of disk-heavy MapReduce stages. 
It also provides high-level APIs like DataFrames and supports both batch and streaming workloads,making it more flexible and efficient.

4) Lazy evaluation in Spark means transformations are not executed immediately but are recorded as a DAG. Execution is triggered only when an action is called, 
allowing Spark to optimize the entire workflow before running it

5)
Transformations → build the plan
👉 Actions → execute the plan
Transformations in Spark are lazy operations that define a DAG of computations without executing them, while actions trigger the execution of that DAG and return results.
Each action results in a separate job

6) A DAG in Spark is a logical execution plan representing a sequence of transformations. It is created during lazy evaluation and optimized before execution, 
then divided into stages and tasks for parallel processing

7) Spark achieves fault tolerance using lineage-based recomputation. It tracks transformations as a DAG, so if a partition is lost due to task or executor failure, 
it can be recomputed. Additionally, Spark retries failed tasks and can use checkpointing to avoid long recomputation chains

8) In Apache Spark, lineage refers to the sequence of transformations applied to an RDD or DataFrame, represented as a DAG.
Spark uses this lineage to recompute lost data in case of failures instead of storing intermediate results, which provides efficient fault tolerance.

9) SparkSession is the unified entry point in Spark that allows users to create DataFrames, run SQL queries, and manage configurations.
It replaces older contexts like SparkContext, SQLContext, and HiveContext, providing a single interface to interact with Spark

10) SparkContext is the low-level entry point used for RDD-based operations and cluster communication, while SparkSession is a higher-level 
unified interface introduced in Spark 2.0 that supports DataFrames, SQL, and configuration management,and internally uses SparkContext

11) RDD is the fundamental data structure in Spark, representing an immutable, distributed collection of data that can be processed in parallel.
It provides fault tolerance through lineage and supports lazy evaluation, but is mostly replaced by DataFrames in modern applications

12) DataFrames are preferred over RDDs in Apache Spark because they provide higher-level abstractions with built-in optimizations like Catalyst Optimizer 
and Tungsten execution engine. This leads to better performance, less memory usage, and simpler code. Additionally, DataFrames support SQL queries and
schema-based processing, whereas RDDs are low-level, lack optimization, and require more manual coding

13)In Apache Spark, Catalyst Optimizer is the query optimization engine used by Spark SQL that analyzes and optimizes 
logical execution plans into efficient physical plans using rule-based and cost-based optimizations

14) Tungsten is the execution engine in Spark that improves performance by optimizing memory management and CPU utilization through techniques 
like off-heap memory usage, binary processing, and code generation

15) In Spark, the Driver is the main program that builds the DAG, schedules tasks, and coordinates execution, while Executors are worker
processes that run tasks in parallel and process data on cluster nodes
